{"post_stream":{"posts":[{"id":3234385,"name":"","username":"robojack","avatar_template":"/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/r/49beb7/{size}.png","created_at":"2023-09-22T20:35:40.114Z","cooked":"<p>I’m working as a (new) mentor for our school’s robotics group.  I worked with the team a little last year but we never got past more than the ability to drive.  Over the summer, I put together a Romi robot and can drive it but I’m trying to program a button to turn on one of the lights just to get a basic understanding.  From what I read, it seems like we should be using triggers to respond to button pushes.  In looking at last year’s programming, there is a section on “Binding Commands to Triggers”   In it they have examples of generic HID, Xbox, PS4 and Joystick using the form<br>
CommandXboxController exampleCommandController = new CommandXboxController(1);<br>
to create the controller and then<br>
Trigger xButton = exampleCommandController.x()<br>
to create the trigger.</p>
<p>In the Romi code they have</p>
<p>private final Joystick m_controller = new Joystick(1);</p>
<p>To use triggers, should I just change this line to</p>
<p>private final CommandJoystick m_controller = new CommandJoystick(1);<br>
and put the trigger below it<br>
Trigger xButton = m_controller.x() ? or Trigger xButton = m_controller.x()</p>
<p>Also what is the x above?  Is it just the number of the button or does it follow the labeling on the joystick?  Is it different for each instance (HID, xbox, ps4, joystick)?</p>
<p>Sorry for newbie questions but I just can’t quite figure this out and I’d appreciate any help I can get.</p>
<p>Thanks</p>","post_number":1,"post_type":1,"posts_count":29,"updated_at":"2023-09-22T20:35:40.114Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":496,"reads":348,"readers_count":347,"score":2549.6,"yours":false,"topic_id":441336,"topic_slug":"programming-triggers-for-joystick-switches","display_username":"","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":null,"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":60576,"hidden":false,"trust_level":1,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":""},"post_url":"/t/programming-triggers-for-joystick-switches/441336/1","custom_user_title":null,"reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null,"can_vote":false},{"id":3234417,"name":"Nelson Green (1108 Mentor Coach Electrical Programming)","username":"ngreen","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/ngreen/{size}/264478_2.png","created_at":"2023-09-22T22:43:26.972Z","cooked":"<p>CommandJoystick has different methods, and doesn’t have an x() method for the “x button” of the controller.  It also doesn’t have any button method other than top() and trigger() (button).  You may need to look to CommandGenericHID and use the method button(int) with int being the button number.  If you don’t know the number, you can usually plug into the driver station and on the joystick page count the position it shows up at.</p>","post_number":2,"post_type":1,"posts_count":29,"updated_at":"2023-09-22T22:43:26.972Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":0,"reads":298,"readers_count":297,"score":59.6,"yours":false,"topic_id":441336,"topic_slug":"programming-triggers-for-joystick-switches","display_username":"Nelson Green (1108 Mentor Coach Electrical Programming)","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":"","bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":2695,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":""},"post_url":"/t/programming-triggers-for-joystick-switches/441336/2","custom_user_title":null,"reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null},{"id":3234431,"name":"Richard Budop","username":"rickmaster","avatar_template":"/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/r/ee7513/{size}.png","created_at":"2023-09-23T00:19:57.305Z","cooked":"<p>We use a generic joystick object for our custom button box which works a lot like a generic joystick. Here is how we declare our joystick.</p>
<pre><code class="lang-auto">private Joystick operatorJoystick = new Joystick(2);
</code></pre>
<p>Then when we configure our button bindings we declare our buttons like this:</p>
<pre><code class="lang-auto">    joystickButton operator1 = new JoystickButton(operatorJoystick, 1);
    JoystickButton operator2 = new JoystickButton(operatorJoystick, 2);
    JoystickButton operator3 = new JoystickButton(operatorJoystick, 3);
    JoystickButton operator4 = new JoystickButton(operatorJoystick, 4);
    JoystickButton operator5 = new JoystickButton(operatorJoystick, 5);
    JoystickButton operator6 = new JoystickButton(operatorJoystick, 6);
    JoystickButton operator7 = new JoystickButton(operatorJoystick, 7);
    JoystickButton operator8 = new JoystickButton(operatorJoystick, 8);
    JoystickButton operator9 = new JoystickButton(operatorJoystick, 9);
    JoystickButton operator10 = new JoystickButton(operatorJoystick, 10);
    JoystickButton operator11 = new JoystickButton(operatorJoystick, 11);
    JoystickButton operator12 = new JoystickButton(operatorJoystick, 12);

    Trigger coneTrigger = new Trigger(s_StateController::isConeMode);
    Trigger cubeTrigger = new Trigger(s_StateController::isCubeMode);
</code></pre>
<p>Then we use the button bindings like this:</p>
<pre><code class="lang-auto">    operator1.onTrue(new InstantCommand(() -&gt; s_Intake.runIntake()));
    operator1.and(intakeSensorTrigger).onTrue(new InstantCommand(() -&gt; s_Intake.stopIntake()));

    operator1.onFalse(new InstantCommand(() -&gt; s_Intake.stopIntake()));
    operator2.onTrue(new InstantCommand(() -&gt; s_Intake.hingeTo(Constants.IntakeConstants.hingeDown)));

    operator7.onTrue(new SetCubeMode(s_LED));
    operator8.onTrue(new SetConeMode(s_LED));

    operator9.and(coneTrigger).onTrue(new HomePositionCone());
    operator10.and(coneTrigger).onTrue(new ArmHigh());
    operator11.and(coneTrigger).onTrue(new ArmMedium());
    operator12.and(coneTrigger).onTrue(new ArmLow());

</code></pre>
<p>We used the driver station on the controller menu to determine what each button’s number was.<br>
Included some different examples of the different ways we used button bindings to call instant commands and some actual commands, as well as when in junction with some customer triggers.</p>
<p>Hope this is similar enough to what you are trying to do.</p>","post_number":3,"post_type":1,"posts_count":29,"updated_at":"2023-09-23T00:19:57.305Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":4,"reads":281,"readers_count":280,"score":121.2,"yours":false,"topic_id":441336,"topic_slug":"programming-triggers-for-joystick-switches","display_username":"Richard Budop","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":"","bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[{"id":2,"count":3}],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":34431,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":"3604 Programming Mentor and Alum "},"post_url":"/t/programming-triggers-for-joystick-switches/441336/3","custom_user_title":"3604 Programming Mentor and Alum ","reactions":[{"id":"heart","type":"emoji","count":3}],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":3,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null},{"id":3234433,"name":"UnofficialForth","username":"UnofficialForth","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/unofficialforth/{size}/167902_2.png","created_at":"2023-09-23T01:06:55.555Z","cooked":"<aside class="quote no-group quote-modified" data-username="robojack" data-post="1" data-topic="441336" data-full="true">
